{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="guide-hiring-an-accountant-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;Hiring an accountant,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>&ldquo;Accountant&rdquo; is a loose word people use for everyone who touches their numbers, but in practice it covers four distinct roles. A <strong>bookkeeper</strong> handles the operational ledger &mdash; recording transactions, categorizing expenses, reconciling bank and credit-card accounts, running payroll entries, and producing month-end reports &mdash; so the file is always accurate and current. A <strong>CPA</strong> (Certified Public Accountant) is a state-licensed accountant who can prepare and sign tax returns, perform attest work like audits and reviews, and give formal tax and financial advice. An <strong>enrolled agent (EA)</strong> is licensed by the IRS specifically for tax: returns, planning, and representing you in an audit or collections matter. A <strong>fractional CFO</strong> works above all of this on strategy &mdash; forecasting, cash-flow planning, pricing, and raising capital &mdash; on a part-time basis.</p>
      <p>Hiring well means matching the role to the job, not chasing the most impressive title. The honest reality for most small businesses: you need clean, current books year-round (a bookkeeper) and a tax return filed once a year (a CPA or EA). Those are two different hires, and the bookkeeping is what makes the tax work fast and cheap. That&rsquo;s where we fit &mdash; we keep the books CPA-ready and coordinate the handoff. When what you actually need is the return itself, or tax advice, the right hire is a CPA or EA, and we&rsquo;ll tell you so.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

